2026-05-16 18:41:41 | DEBUG | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Model response #5 [role=assistant block=1 tool_use] execute_ideal({"intent": "Compute Pearson correlation between ancient Roman city rank (averaging 'a or b' ranges) and population-rank of matched modern cities (population>1M). Match ancient to modern by nearest within 0.1 degrees; if multiple ancient samples match, take last sample in data. For modern population rank, rank modern cities by population descending among those >1M; then compute correlation between ancient rank and modern population rank for matched pairs; output to 6 decimals.", "dataset_id": "kramabench-archeology-hard-7", "file_path": "files/roman_cities.csv", "code": "import pandas as pd, re, numpy as np\nroman = pd.read_csv('s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-hard-7/files/roman_cities.csv')\nmodern = pd.read_csv('s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-hard-12/files/worldcities.csv')\n# Prepare modern cities filter >1M\nmodern = modern.copy()\nmodern['population'] = pd.to_numeric(modern['population'], errors='coerce')\nmodern = modern[modern['population']>1_000_000].copy()\nmodern['lat']=pd.to_numeric(modern['lat'], errors='coerce')\nmodern['lng']=pd.to_numeric(modern['lng'], errors='coerce')\nmodern = modern.dropna(subset=['lat','lng','population'])\nmodern = modern.reset_index(drop=True)\n# population rank: 1 highest\nmodern['modern_pop_rank'] = modern['population'].rank(method='first', ascending=False).astype(int)\n# Prepare ancient rank numeric with or-range\nrank_col='Barrington Atlas Rank'\nroman = roman.copy()\n# last sample in data: keep last occurrence per match later\nroman['lat']=pd.to_numeric(roman['Latitude (Y)'], errors='coerce')\nroman['lng']=pd.to_numeric(roman['Longitude (X)'], errors='coerce')\nroman = roman.dropna(subset=['lat','lng'])\nroman['anc_rank_num']=roman[rank_col].astype(str)\n# clean like '4 or 5'\n\ndef parse_rank(s):\n    s=s.strip()\n    # handle patterns with ' or '\n    m=re.match(r'^(\\d+)\\s*or\\s*(\\d+)$', s)\n    if m:\n        return (int(m.group(1))+int(m.group(2)))/2\n    # else take first number\n    m=re.search(r'(\\d+)', s)\n    return float(m.group(1)) if m else np.nan\nroman['anc_rank']=roman['anc_rank_num'].apply(parse_rank)\nroman=roman.dropna(subset=['anc_rank'])\n# Match by distance<0.1 degrees; compute pairwise efficiently using brute force (small). modern count ~ few 45k, roman 1467 => 66M ok in numpy.\nR=roman[['lat','lng']].to_numpy()\nM=modern[['lat','lng']].to_numpy()\n# Compute squared distance in degrees euclidean\n# Use broadcasting in chunks to limit memory\nmatches=[]\nchunk=200\nfor i in range(0,len(M),chunk):\n    Mb=M[i:i+chunk]\n    # dist^2: (R-M)^2\n    diff_lat=R[:,0][:,None]-Mb[:,0][None,:]\n    diff_lng=R[:,1][:,None]-Mb[:,1][None,:]\n    dist2=diff_lat**2+diff_lng**2\n    mask=dist2 < (0.1**2)\n    # for each modern j in chunk with matches, record all roman indices\n    for j in range(mask.shape[1]):\n        roman_idxs=np.where(mask[:,j])[0]\n        if roman_idxs.size>0:\n            # take last sample in data => roman_idxs max index (since original order preserved)\n            last_idx=roman_idxs.max()\n            matches.append((i+j,last_idx))\n# Create mapping modern idx -> matched roman idx\nmatch_df=pd.DataFrame(matches, columns=['modern_idx','roman_idx']).drop_duplicates('modern_idx', keep='first')\n# For each modern, take last roman idx already; ensure duplicates resolved\nmatch_df=match_df.sort_values('modern_idx')\nanc_vals=roman.loc[match_df['roman_idx'], 'anc_rank'].to_numpy()\npop_rank=modern.loc[match_df['modern_idx'], 'modern_pop_rank'].to_numpy()\n# Pearson correlation\ncorr=np.corrcoef(anc_vals, pop_rank)[0,1]\ncorr\n"}) [toolUseId=call_9L85G4EYgEAHmfsDkiqC6WSs]
